<span id="vi.xx-p11"></span> The narratives given by Paul himself of his
conversion in [Acts 22:0](../../../bib/kjv/act022.htm#000.md), [Acts
26:0](../../../bib/kjv/act026.htm#000.md)<span
id="vi.xx-p11.1"></span>[Acts
xxii.](../../../bib/kjv/act022.htm#000.md)<span id="vi.xx-p11.2"></span>
and Acts xxvi. as well as allusion to the subjects in his epistles,
present some harmonistic difficulties, which have, however, been greatly
exaggerated by a criticism which is unfavorable to the historical
character of the Acts. The constant factors in all the accounts are: the
light from heaven, the voice of Jesus and Saul’s answer, and the solemn
charge commissioning Saul to bear the name of Christ to the Gentiles. In
[Acts xxvi](../../../bib/kjv/act026.htm#000.md)<span
id="vi.xx-p11.3"></span>. the interview with Ananias is omitted; in
[Acts 22](../../../bib/kjv/act022.htm#000.md)<span
id="vi.xx-p11.4"></span>. it is narrated, but the occasion of Ananias’
going to Saul is not given; in [Acts
9](../../../bib/kjv/act009.htm#000.md)<span id="vi.xx-p11.5"></span>. the
Lord is represented as speaking to him and bidding him go, and it is
affirmed that at the same time Saul has a vision of his coming. In [Acts
22](../../../bib/kjv/act022.htm#000.md)<span id="vi.xx-p11.6"></span>. the
address of Ananias is considerably more extended than in [Acts
9](../../../bib/kjv/act009.htm#000.md)<span id="vi.xx-p11.7"></span>. Some
minor points of difference have been noted, as: in [Acts
9.7](../../../bib/kjv/act009.htm#007.md)<span id="vi.xx-p11.8"></span> it
is said that Saul’s companions heard the voice but saw no one, while in
[Acts 22.9](../../../bib/kjv/act022.htm#009.md)<span
id="vi.xx-p11.9"></span>, it is said that they saw the light but heard
not the voice of Him who spoke. The discrepancy is resolved by many by
translating <span class="Greek"><span
id="vi.xx-p11.10"></span>ἤ</span><span class="Greek"><span
id="vi.xx-p11.11"></span>κουσαν</span>([Acts
22.9](../../../bib/kjv/act022.htm#009)<span id="vi.xx-p11.12"></span>.md)
“understood”—an admissable sense (so, Lechler, Hackett, Lange). It is
certainly an unwarranted criticism which rejects the common matter of
the various narratives upon the ground of such incidental variations in
the traditions in which a great and mysterious experience has been
preserved.—G.B.S.

<span id="fn_479"></span>[i:480](1110025.htm#fr_479.md) <span
id="vi.xx-p12.1"></span>

