<span id="vi.xx-p18"></span> It is noticeable that in [Acts
22.17](../../../bib/kjv/act022.htm#017.md)<span id="vi.xx-p18.1"></span>,
Paul is reported as connecting his going to Jerusalem directly with the
narrative of his conversion, while in <span
id="vi.xx-p18.2"></span>[Gal. 1:16](../../../bib/kjv/gal001.htm#016.md),
[17](../../../bib/kjv/gal001.htm#017.md)<span id="vi.xx-p18.3"></span> he
states that it was not until three years after his conversion that he
went up to Jerusalem. The various notices can only be matched together
on the view that the coming to Jerusalem mentioned in [Acts
9.26](../../../bib/kjv/act009.htm#026.md)<span id="vi.xx-p18.4"></span> was
the same as that of [Gal. i. 18](../../../bib/kjv/gal001.htm#018.md)<span
id="vi.xx-p18.5"></span>, and that this occurred about three years after
his conversion. The <span class="Greek"><span
id="vi.xx-p18.6"></span>ἡ</span><span class="Greek"><span
id="vi.xx-p18.7"></span>μέραι ἱκαναί</span> of [Acts
9.23](../../../bib/kjv/act009.htm#023.md)<span id="vi.xx-p18.8"></span>
must therefore include the time spent in Arabia ([Gal. i.
17](../../../bib/kjv/gal001.htm#017)<span id="vi.xx-p18.9"></span>.md).,
after which Paul must have returned to Damascus, before going up to
Jerusalem. In this way the narratives can be harmonized without
admitting a contradiction (as Baur, Zeller, De Wette); it is probable,
however, that Luke did not know of the visit to Arabia, but connected
Paul’s going to Jerusalem closely with his conversion.—G.B.S.

<span id="fn_484"></span>[i:485](1110025.htm#fr_484.md) <span
